  <section>
    <h3>Franchises and Platforms:</h3>
    <p>
      By now an overall framework should be taking shape with regards to the categories and their respective GET request methods.
      To finish off this overview, and to cement the idea that the real strength of the api lies more within the request type than a
      specific category, here are the following methods for both the franchise and platform requests as well as an example for each.
    </p>
    <section>
      <h4>Franchise:</h4>
      <p>
        The franchise category groups games that are intentionally designed to be related to each other in some way. Such as the Call
        of Duty franchise or the Legend of Zelda franchise. Here is a list of its GET requests:
        <li>/franchises: Returns a list of all franchises from the database.</li>
        <li>/franchises/meta: Returns the meta data for the franchises category.</li>
        <li>/franchises/{franchiseid}: Returns a franchise object matching the franchise id.</li>
        <li>/franchises/{franchiseid}/games: Returns a list of games that belongs to a certain franchise.</li>
        <br>
        Here is an example of a franchise object:
      </p>
      <pre>
        <code>
          {
            "franchise": {
             "id": 9,
            "name": "Tom Clancy",
            "slug": "tom-clancy"
            }
          }
        </code>
      </pre>
    </section>
    <br>
    <section>
      <h4>Platforms:</h4>
      <p>
        The platform category can make requests for all of the different video game platforms and return there relevant information:
        <li>/platforms: Returns a list of all platforms from the database.</li>
        <li>/platforms/meta: Returns the meta data for the platforms category.</li>
        <li>/platforms/{platformid}: Returns a platform object matching the platform id.</li>
        <li>/platforms/{platformid}/games: Returns a list of games that belongs to a certain platform.</li>
        For the most part you would really only use either the "/platforms" or "/platforms/{platformid}/games" GET request to either
        see a list of all platforms that are stored in the data base, or what games would be associated with a given platform. But to
        show specifically whats in a platform JSON Object, the following response was retreived with the "/platforms/{platformid}":
      </p>
      <pre>
        <code>
          {
            "platform": {
            "id": 67,
            "name": "Intellivision",
            "slug": "intellivision"
            }
          }
        </code>
      </pre>
    </section>
  </section>
